### Component Renderings (created via `create_content_item`)

Renderings link Sitecore items to front-end React components and enable them in the Pages editor.

**Location:** `/sitecore/layout/Renderings/Project/<site-collection>/`
**Template:** JSON Rendering (Template ID: `04646a89-996f-4ee7-878a-ffdbf1f0ef0d`)

**Rendering Folder Structure:**

Like templates, renderings must be organized into category subfolders that mirror the template folder structure. Use Rendering Folder items to create the hierarchy.

```
/sitecore/layout/Renderings/Project/<site-collection>/
  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Banners/
  ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Hero (JSON Rendering)
  ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ HeroBanner (JSON Rendering)
  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Cards/
  ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ ArticleCards (JSON Rendering)
  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Navigation/
  ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Header (JSON Rendering)
  ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Footer (JSON Rendering)
  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Forms/
      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ ContactForm (JSON Rendering)
```

**Key rules for rendering folder organization:**
- Mirror the template `Components/` subfolder structure ‚Äî if the template is under `Components/Cards/`, put the rendering under `Cards/`
- One rendering per component ‚Äî the rendering name matches the component (e.g., "ArticleCards" rendering for the ArticleCards component)
- Check existing folder structure first with `get_content_item_by_path` before creating new folders

#### CRITICAL FIELDS (all required):

**1. `componentName` ‚Äî MUST use kebab-case matching the component filename**

The `componentName` field must match the component-map key exactly, which uses kebab-case derived from the filename.

**Naming Convention Chain (all must match):**

```
Component file:        article-cards.tsx       (kebab-case)
Component-map import:  import * as articlecards from '...'
Component-map key:     ['article-cards', { ...articlecards }]
Rendering field:       componentName: "article-cards"   ‚Üê MUST MATCH MAP KEY
```

Examples:
- ‚úÖ `"article-cards"` ‚Äî matches `article-cards.tsx` and map key
- ‚úÖ `"hero"` ‚Äî matches `hero.tsx` and map key
- ‚ùå `"ArticleCards"` ‚Äî PascalCase does not match
- ‚ùå `"articlecards"` ‚Äî missing hyphen

**2. `Datasource Template` ‚Äî Complete path to the datasource template (NOT a GUID)**

This tells Sitecore what template to use when creating new datasources and what data structure to expect.

Format: `/sitecore/templates/Project/<site-collection>/Path/To/Template`

Examples:
- ‚úÖ `/sitecore/templates/Project/mysite/Components/Cards/ArticleCards`
- ‚úÖ `/sitecore/templates/Project/click-click-launch/Components/Banners/Hero`
- ‚ùå `/sitecore/templates/Project/mysite/ArticleCards` ‚Äî missing category subfolder
- ‚ùå `{e0bd6abd-50c2-429a-baa0-ed13517e7055}` ‚Äî GUID format not accepted
- ‚ùå Empty ‚Äî causes "No datasource template found" error

**3. `Datasource Location` ‚Äî Query defining where datasources can be stored and selected**

Uses Sitecore query syntax with `@@name` and `@@templatename`. Multiple locations are separated with pipe `|`.

**Common Query Patterns:**

Site-specific only:
```
query:$site/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Hero Folder']
```

Site + shared sites:
```
query:$site/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Hero Folder']|query:$sharedSites/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Hero Folder']
```

With nested folder structure:
```
query:$site/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Hero Sections Folder']|query:$sharedSites/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Hero Sections Folder']
```

**Query Syntax Breakdown:**
- `$site` ‚Äî Current site content root
- `$sharedSites` ‚Äî Shared content root across sites
- `/*[@@name='Data']` ‚Äî Match child item named "Data"
- `/*[@@templatename='Hero Folder']` ‚Äî Match children using the specified folder template
- `|` ‚Äî OR separator for multiple query locations

**4. `Data source` ‚Äî Leave EMPTY** (do not set a template ID here)

**5. `Parameters Template` ‚Äî Optional**, for component-level parameters

**6. `AddFieldEditorButton` ‚Äî Set to `"1"`** to enable the field editor button in Pages

**7. `Component GraphQL Query` (internal MCP field name: `ComponentQuery`) ‚Äî REQUIRED for components with parent/children datasource structures**

This field shapes the JSON data passed to the component. Variables `$datasource`, `$contextItem`, and `$language` are always available. If left blank, normal JSS shaping is used ‚Äî but for any component that has a parent datasource with child items (list-based components), you MUST provide a GraphQL query that fetches both the parent fields and the children fields.

**Important:** The Content Editor UI label shows "Component GraphQL Query", but when updating the rendering via MCP (e.g., `update_content` with `itemId`, `siteName`, `fields`), use the internal field name `ComponentQuery` in the fields payload.

**When to use vs. when to leave empty:**

- **Use a Component GraphQL Query** only when the component has a parent/children (list) datasource and needs `children.results` in props. Examples: ArticleCards, MultiPromo, FAQ lists, card grids with child items.
- **Leave Component GraphQL Query empty** for single-datasource components with no children (e.g., Hero, Promo, simple Banners). The layout service will use default JSS shaping and a different props shape (see "Props Shape: With vs Without Component GraphQL Query" below).

When the component does not need children functionality, do not add a GraphQL query to the rendering; leave the field empty.

**Why this is critical:** Without this query, the component will only receive the parent datasource fields and will NOT receive the children data. The `children { results { ... } }` block in the query is what makes child items available to the React component via `fields.data.datasource.children.results`.

**Query Structure:**
- The query name should match the parent template name
- Use `$datasource` and `$language` as query variables
- Use `... on <ParentTemplateName>` to type the parent and access its fields
- Use `children { results { ... on <ChildTemplateName> { } } }` to fetch child items
- Every field you want available in the React component must be explicitly listed with `{ jsonValue }`

**Example ‚Äî MultiPromo (parent with SimplePromo children):**

```graphql
query MultiPromo($datasource: String!, $language: String!) {
  datasource: item(path: $datasource, language: $language) {
    ... on MultiPromo {
      title {
        jsonValue
      }
      description {
        jsonValue
      }
    }
    children {
      results {
        ... on SimplePromo {
          id
          heading {
            jsonValue
          }
          image {
            jsonValue
          }
          link {
            jsonValue
          }
          description {
            jsonValue
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Example ‚Äî ArticleCards (parent with ArticleCard children):**

```graphql
query ArticleCards($datasource: String!, $language: String!) {
  datasource: item(path: $datasource, language: $language) {
    ... on ArticleCards {
      title {
        jsonValue
      }
    }
    children {
      results {
        ... on ArticleCard {
          id
          title {
            jsonValue
          }
          image {
            jsonValue
          }
          link {
            jsonValue
          }
          badgeText {
            jsonValue
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Key Rules for the GraphQL Query:**
- Template type names in `... on <TemplateName>` use PascalCase matching the Sitecore template name
- Field names in the query use camelCase (e.g., `badgeText` not `BadgeText`)
- Always include `id` in children results so React can use it as a key
- Always wrap each field with `{ jsonValue }` so the Content SDK can render them as editable
- If a field is missing from the query, it will NOT be available in the component props
- The query alias `datasource:` must be used for the root `item()` call

**Common Mistakes:**
- ‚ùå Leaving this field blank for list components ‚Äî children data will be missing. For list components, you must set the query and use `fields.data.datasource` and `datasource.children.results` in the component.
- ‚ùå Adding a GraphQL query to a simple component (e.g., Hero) that has no children ‚Äî unnecessary and changes the props shape. Leave it empty and use the default PascalCase/`.value` shape.
- ‚ùå Forgetting `{ jsonValue }` on fields ‚Äî fields won't be editable in Pages
- ‚ùå Using wrong template name in `... on` fragments ‚Äî data won't resolve
- ‚ùå Omitting `id` from children ‚Äî React will lack unique keys for list rendering
- ‚ùå Writing a component with `fields.data.datasource` and `jsonValue` when the rendering has no query ‚Äî the component will receive `fields.Title`, `fields.Description` with `.value` instead
- ‚ùå Looking for children at `fields.data.children.results` (sibling to datasource) ‚Äî children are nested **inside** datasource: `fields.data.datasource.children.results`

#### Complete Rendering Example:

```
Name: ArticleCards
Location: /sitecore/layout/Renderings/Project/mysite/Cards/ArticleCards
Template: JSON Rendering
Fields:
  componentName:          article-cards
  Datasource Template:    /sitecore/templates/Project/mysite/Components/Cards/ArticleCards
  Datasource Location:    query:$site/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Article Cards Folder']|query:$sharedSites/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Article Cards Folder']
  Data source:            (empty)
  AddFieldEditorButton:   1
  ComponentQuery:         query ArticleCards($datasource: String!, $language: String!) { datasource: item(path: $datasource, language: $language) { ... on ArticleCards { title { jsonValue } } children { results { ... on ArticleCard { id title { jsonValue } image { jsonValue } link { jsonValue } badgeText { jsonValue } } } } } }
```

Note: The field is labeled "Component GraphQL Query" in the Content Editor UI, but use `ComponentQuery` as the field name when setting it via MCP.

#### Creation Workflow:

```
1. Create rendering (inside the correct category folder):
   create_content_item(
     name="ArticleCards",
     templateId="04646a89-996f-4ee7-878a-ffdbf1f0ef0d",
     parentId="<cards-renderings-folder-id>"
   )

2. Update rendering fields (use update_content or update_fields_on_content_item):
   update_content(
     itemId="<rendering-id>",
     siteName="mysite",
     fields={
       "componentName": "article-cards",
       "Datasource Template": "/sitecore/templates/Project/mysite/Components/Cards/ArticleCards",
       "Datasource Location": "query:$site/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Article Cards Folder']|query:$sharedSites/*[@@name='Data']/*[@@templatename='Article Cards Folder']",
       "AddFieldEditorButton": "1",
       "ComponentQuery": "query ArticleCards($datasource: String!, $language: String!) { datasource: item(path: $datasource, language: $language) { ... on ArticleCards { title { jsonValue } } children { results { ... on ArticleCard { id title { jsonValue } image { jsonValue } link { jsonValue } badgeText { jsonValue } } } } } }"
     }
   )
```

**Note on updating items via MCP:** To update rendering or content item fields, use whichever MCP update tool is available: `update_content` (accepts `itemId`, `siteName`, `fields`) or `update_fields_on_content_item` (accepts `itemId`, `fields`). Both achieve the same result. For the GraphQL query field, always use the internal field name `ComponentQuery` in the payload, not the UI label "Component GraphQL Query".

